We first extract the key figures from each statement. Note that all amounts are taken at the end date as provided:

Step 1. Calculate Debt to Equity Ratio  
• From the balance sheet, Total Owner’s Equity = 11,657,959.24  
• Total Liabilities can be derived as:  
  Total Liabilities = Total Assets – Total Owner’s Equity  
  = 15,086,049.65 – 11,657,959.24  
  = 3,428,090.41  
• Debt to Equity Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Owner’s Equity  
  = 3,428,090.41 / 11,657,959.24  
  ≈ 0.29

Step 2. Calculate Net Profit Margin  
• From the income statement, Net Profit = –1,342,040.76 and Total Revenue = 8,361,807.77  
• Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
  = (–1,342,040.76 / 8,361,807.77) × 100  
  ≈ –16.05%

Step 3. Calculate Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio  
• From the cash flow statement, Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –4,900,875.61 and Total Current Liabilities = 3,428,090.41  
• Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio = Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities / Total Current Liabilities  
  = –4,900,875.61 / 3,428,090.41  
  ≈ –1.43

Thus, the final answer is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.29",
    "Net Profit Margin": "-16.05%",
    "operating cash flow to current liabilities ratio": "-1.43"
  }
}
